  "prompt": "What is Google's internal code review policy/process?",
  "response": "Google's internal code review policy and process are not publicly disclosed in detail, as they are part of the company's internal practices. However, based on general knowledge and information from former employees, I can provide a high-level overview of what such a process typically entails at Google.\n\n### Google's Code Review Process - General Overview\n\n1. **Pre-Commit Review:**\n   - **Code Writing:** Developers write code in their local environment or within Google's internal development environment.\n   - **Unit Tests:** Before submitting code for review, developers are generally required to write and run unit tests to ensure the code functions as expected.\n\n2. **Code Submission:**\n   - **Code Review Tool:** Google uses an internal tool called \"Critique\" for code reviews. Developers submit their code changes through this tool, which creates a review request.\n   - **Change Description:** Developers provide a detailed description of the changes, explaining the purpose and any relevant context.\n\n3. **Review Assignment:**\n   - **Reviewers:** The code is assigned to one or more reviewers, typically including the team lead and other relevant team members who are familiar with the codebase.\n   - **Automated Checks:** Some automated checks may run to catch basic issues like style violations or obvious bugs.\n\n4. **Review Process:**\n   - **Feedback Loop:** Reviewers examine the code and provide feedback, which can include suggestions for improvement, questions, or approval.\n   - **Iterations:** The developer may need to make changes based on the feedback and resubmit the code for another round of reviews. This process can repeat multiple times until the code is deemed satisfactory.\n\n5. **Approval and Merge:**\n   - **Final Approval:** Once the code is approved by the necessary reviewers, it can be merged into the main codebase.\n   - **Continuous Integration:** The code then goes through continuous integration and deployment processes to ensure it works well with the existing system.\n\n6. **Post-Commit Review:**\n   - **Monitoring:** After the code is merged, it is monitored for any unforeseen issues or bugs.\n   - **Documentation:** Developers are often required to update documentation and ensure that any related processes or systems are updated accordingly.\n\n### Key Principles\n\n- **Quality and Reliability:** Emphasis on writing high-quality, reliable code that adheres to Google's coding standards.\n- **Collaboration:** Encouraging collaboration and knowledge sharing among team members.\n- **Security:** Ensuring code changes do not introduce security vulnerabilities.\n- **Efficiency:** Streamlining the review process to minimize delays while maintaining high standards.\n\n### Additional Notes\n\n- **Training:** New hires and interns receive training on the code review process and are often paired with mentors.\n- **Tools and Automation:** Google invests heavily in tools and automation to make the code review process more efficient and effective.\n\nWhile this is a general outline, the specifics can vary based on the team, project, and other factors. For detailed and up-to-date information, one would need access to Google's internal documentation and processes.",
